:"–1282","1260–1355":"1260–1355","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1295–1327":"1295–1327","1297–Male":"1297–Deceased","1299–Male":"1299–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1289":"1289","1355":"1355","1266":"1266","1299":"1299","1320":"1320","about 1299":"about 1299","about 1295":"about 1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Aldersey, Cheshire, England":"Aldersey, Cheshire, England","Wrenbury, Cheshire, England":"Wrenbury, Cheshire, England","Northwich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northwich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hatton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatten","meanings":["English: variant of   Hatton  . This surname is also common among African Americans.","North German: habitational name from the name of an area of marshland between Oldenburg and Bremen."]},{"name":"Hattan","meanings":["English and Scottish (Argyll): variant of   Hatton  ."]},{"name":"Aton","meanings":["variant of   Hatton  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>).","English:"]},{"name":"Heath","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) heath’ (Middle English <i>he(a)th</i>, Old English <i>hǣth</i>) or else a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. The same word also denoted heather, the characteristic plant of heathland areas. This surname has also been established in Dublin, Ireland, since the late 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":24,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":49,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":62,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Hatton was born in 1266, in Chester, Cheshire, England, her father, Sir Simon de Hatton, was 26 and her mother, Margaret Goldborne, was 47. She married Adam de Aldersey in 1289. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1360, in Aldersey, Cheshire, England, at the age of 94."},"et":{"1266–1360":"1266–1360","–1282":"–1282","1260–1355":"1260–1355","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1295–1327":"1295–1327","1297–Male":"1297–Surnud","1299–Male":"1299–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1289":"1289","1355":"1355","1266":"1266","1299":"1299","1320":"1320","about 1299":"umbes 1299","about 1295":"umbes 1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Aldersey, Cheshire, England":"Aldersey, Cheshire, England","Wrenbury, Cheshire, England":"Wrenbury, Cheshire, England","Northwich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northwich, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1266–1360":"1266–1360","–1282":"–1282","1260–1355":"1260–1355","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1295–1327":"1295–1327","1297–Male":"1297–Kuollut","1299–Male":"1299–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1289":"1289","1355":"1355","1266":"1266","1299":"1299","1320":"1320","about 1299":"noin 1299","about 1295":"noin 1295","1328":"1328","13